    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_881627314" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/881627314" />
    <a title="Ben" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9592279-ben"><img alt="Ben" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1533140387p2/9592279.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/881627314?book_show_action=true">Mar 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben" href="/user/show/9592279-ben">Ben</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer881627314" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer215423965283519078">I think that I was familiar with the legend of Don Juan, as are many of us in Western culture, long before I had ever seen any films or read any works about legend. It has become a sort of folktale passed down by word of mouth over the years, and it has been reinterpreted by many playwrights and poets. The first work that I encountered based on the story of Don Juan was Shaw&apos;s <i>Man and Superman,</i> which I read during my Shaw period many years ago (one of my favorite playwrights whose works I really</span>
  <span id="freeText215423965283519078" style="display:none">I think that I was familiar with the legend of Don Juan, as are many of us in Western culture, long before I had ever seen any films or read any works about legend. It has become a sort of folktale passed down by word of mouth over the years, and it has been reinterpreted by many playwrights and poets. The first work that I encountered based on the story of Don Juan was Shaw's <i>Man and Superman,</i> which I read during my Shaw period many years ago (one of my favorite playwrights whose works I really need to revisit soon), and I remember this play having a strong impact on me then, particularly the scene with Don Juan (Tanner) in Hell. I was aware at this time about the treatment of the legend by Molière and Byron but this now is my first time reading any other author's take on the legend since I first read Shaw's wonderful play nearly ten years ago(!). <br /><br />I was less moved by Molière's interpretation than by Shaw's, with its modern twist, which I found a bit deeper on a philosophical level. But Molière's telling is still very entertaining, particularly due to the character of Sganarelle (his asides and final speech especially), a comic character often played by Molière himself and equally inseparable from the body of Molière's comedy as Sir John Falstaff is from the works of Shakespeare. <br /><br />The criticisms of religious hypocrisy were already dealt with in Molière's <i>Tartuffe,</i> and if the controversy caused by that work (only a year before) was not still fresh, Molière revived it in this play (notably in Don Juan's monologue in Act V). One can't help but to think when reading this 17th century genius that he was undoubtedly ahead of his time, never afraid to cause ripples in the water (but unfortunately often having to compromise his artistic vision due to societal pressures). </span>
  <a data-text-id="215423965283519078" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


