    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_372203179" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/372203179" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11077996-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524363330p2/11077996.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/372203179?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/11077996-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer372203179" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7712230673118486566">The Don Juan myth is excellent material for one who can pull the strings on the emotions of his audience like Moliere. He enjoys and makes deliberate use of the force of identification. The Don Juan mentality resides in many heads, whether one is aware or not, as a driver of fantasies. In the majority of cases, one would love to live this life if it were not for the lack of some requisite stuff, e.g. looks, height, social skills, charm. As in Tartuffe, Moliere&apos;s skilled use of a detestable chara</span>
  <span id="freeText7712230673118486566" style="display:none">The Don Juan myth is excellent material for one who can pull the strings on the emotions of his audience like Moliere. He enjoys and makes deliberate use of the force of identification. The Don Juan mentality resides in many heads, whether one is aware or not, as a driver of fantasies. In the majority of cases, one would love to live this life if it were not for the lack of some requisite stuff, e.g. looks, height, social skills, charm. As in Tartuffe, Moliere's skilled use of a detestable character gives this play its legs, and he couples it with an attack on hypocrisy for added push. Francois de la Rochefoucauld, a contemporary of Moliere, lamented the incongruity of deeds, words, and formalities judging by how much the topic dominated his Maxims. I guess it was a significant problem then. Then again, it always is. Don't you wish everyone would just be real with each other? Well, Moliere definitely did. It certainly goes a long way in making his plays so refreshing. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7712230673118486566" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

