<div id="review_1792008978" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1792008978" />
    <a title="Libellus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27589180-libellus"><img alt="Libellus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603762333p2/27589180.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1792008978?book_show_action=true">Oct 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Libellus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Libellus" href="/user/show/27589180-libellus">Libellus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1792008978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7564381112644377085">Don Juan by Molière<br/>October 2016<br/>3/5<br/>*Read as part of my Cegep 1 (grade 12) French literature class*<br/>*Read in the original French*<br/><br/>After seeing Tartuffe at the Théâtre du Nouveau-Monde (Montreal) on Thursday, I read Don Juan, Molière’s other famous play. I have to say I enjoyed it a lot more than Tartuffe. It was cleverly funny and the characters were obnoxiously great. The huge downfall for this play was the plot. The abrupt ending is to be expected from a classicist play, yet it creates a sense of </span>
  <span id="freeText7564381112644377085" style="display:none">Don Juan by Molière<br />October 2016<br />3/5<br />*Read as part of my Cegep 1 (grade 12) French literature class*<br />*Read in the original French*<br /><br />After seeing Tartuffe at the Théâtre du Nouveau-Monde (Montreal) on Thursday, I read Don Juan, Molière’s other famous play. I have to say I enjoyed it a lot more than Tartuffe. It was cleverly funny and the characters were obnoxiously great. The huge downfall for this play was the plot. The abrupt ending is to be expected from a classicist play, yet it creates a sense of rushed and unpolished ending. The surnaturel element also isn’t mastered and could’ve been developed a lot more. I think The Commander would translate better to a play instead of a book, there is definite room to make something magical about his presence through the staging. Overall, Don Juan is entertaining, but I would not recommend it to someone who wants to dive into the libertinage era, Justine by The Marquis de Sade or Dangerous Liaisons by Laclos would be more appropriate. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7564381112644377085" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


